JavaScript has a sort method...
... but it doesn't always work the way you expect.
['steele', 'colt', 'data structures', 'algorithms'].sort();
// ['algorithms', 'colt', 'data structures', 'steele'] sorted alphabetically :)

[6, 4, 15, 10].sort()
// [10, 15, 4, 6] :(

Built in JS sort turns items into a string and sorts them by the unicode point value.

Telling JavaScript how to sort
    - The built-in sort method accepts an optional comparator function
    - You can use this comparator function to tell JavaScript how you want it to sort
    - The comparator looks at pairs of elements (a and b), determines their sort order based on the return value
        - If it returns a negative number, a should come before b
        - If it returns a positive number, a should come after b
        - If it return 0, a and b are the same as far as the sort is concerned

Examples:

function numberCompare(num1, num2) {
    return num1 - num2;
}
[6, 4, 15, 10].sort(numberCompare);
// [4, 6, 10, 15]


function numberCompare(num1, num2) {
    return num2 - num1;
}
[6, 4, 15, 10].sort(numberCompare);
// [15, 10, 6, 4]


function compareByLen(str1, str2) {
    return str2.length - str1.length;
}
['steele', 'colt', 'data structures', 'algorithms'].sort(compareByLen);
// ['data structures', 'algorithms', 'steele', 'colt']

    